# Preorder Traversal — Doubt Notes

---

## Q1. Why could `vector<int> ans` be declared *locally* in the iterative approach, but not in the recursive one?

**Short answer:** You *can* declare it locally in recursion too, but it breaks unless you manually merge results. Here's why.

### Iterative case (local vector works fine)
```cpp
vector<int> preorderTraversal(TreeNode* root) {
    vector<int> ans;   // declared ONCE
    stack<TreeNode*> st;
    while(...) { ... }
    return ans;
}
```
The function is called **only once** by the outside world. No recursion → `ans` is created once, filled inside the loop, and returned once. No conflicts.

### Recursive case (local vector breaks)
```cpp
vector<int> preorderTraversal(TreeNode* root) {
    vector<int> ans;   // declared HERE — problem!
    if(root) {
        ans.push_back(root->val);
        preorderTraversal(root->left);   // creates a BRAND NEW ans internally!
        preorderTraversal(root->right);  // creates ANOTHER brand new ans!
    }
    return ans;
}
```
Every call to `preorderTraversal` — including every recursive call — gets its **own separate `ans`**. They don't share memory.

**Analogy:** Imagine 3 people, each given their own empty notebook (= local `ans`).
- Root writes its own value in its notebook.
- It calls the left-subtree function → that call gets a *brand-new* notebook, fills it, but when it returns, the root **never captures/reads** that notebook (`preorderTraversal(root->left);` return value is ignored).
- Same story for the right call.

So root's notebook ends up with only ITS own value — nothing from left/right ever gets merged in.

### Fix (if you insist on local vector)
```cpp
vector<int> preorderTraversal(TreeNode* root) {
    vector<int> ans;
    if(root) {
        ans.push_back(root->val);
        vector<int> leftAns  = preorderTraversal(root->left);   // capture result
        vector<int> rightAns = preorderTraversal(root->right);  // capture result
        ans.insert(ans.end(), leftAns.begin(), leftAns.end());  // merge manually
        ans.insert(ans.end(), rightAns.begin(), rightAns.end());
    }
    return ans;
}
```
Works, but clunky (extra copying/merging).

### Why the class-level `ans` is used instead
Declaring `ans` as a **member variable** (outside the function, at class scope) means every recursive call shares the **same vector in memory** — no merging needed, everyone writes into the same notebook.

