## Q3. How is the `stack<TreeNode*> st` actually implemented?

`std::stack` is a **container adapter** in C++ STL — it doesn't implement its own data structure from scratch, but wraps another container to give LIFO (Last-In-First-Out) behavior.

### What is LIFO?
Like a stack of plates: you can only add (push) a plate on TOP, and only remove (pop) the plate currently on TOP. First one down is the last one picked up.

### Underlying container
By default, `std::stack` uses `std::deque` internally:
```cpp
stack<TreeNode*> st;                          // uses deque internally (default)
stack<TreeNode*, vector<TreeNode*>> st2;      // force vector as underlying container
stack<TreeNode*, list<TreeNode*>> st3;        // force linked list as underlying container
```
A `deque` (double-ended queue) allows efficient insertion/removal from both ends — but `stack` only ever touches ONE end (the "top"), hiding the rest of deque's flexibility.

### Key operations used
| Operation | What it does |
|---|---|
| `st.push(x)` | Adds `x` to the top of the stack |
| `st.top()` | Returns (without removing) the current top value |
| `st.pop()` | Removes the top element (returns nothing — `void`) |
| `st.empty()` | `true` if the stack has no elements |

**Important quirk:** `pop()` returns `void`, so you can't write `root = st.pop();`. You must first `top()` to read the value, then `pop()` to remove it:
```cpp
root = st.top();  // look at top value
st.pop();         // then remove it
```

### Visual trace of the iterative approach
Tree:
```
      1
     / \
    2   3
   / \
  4   5
```

| Step | root | Action | Stack after |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | 1 | visit 1, push(3), go left | [3] |
| 2 | 2 | visit 2, push(5), go left | [3, 5] |
| 3 | 4 | visit 4, push(NULL, no right child), go left | [3, 5, NULL] |
| 4 | NULL | pop → root=NULL (wasted, harmless) | [3, 5] |
| 5 | NULL | pop → root=5 | [3] |
| 6 | 5 | visit 5, no right, go left | [3] |
| 7 | NULL | pop → root=3 | [] |
| 8 | 3 | visit 3, no right, go left | [] |
| 9 | NULL, stack empty | loop ends | — |

**Final answer:** `1, 2, 4, 5, 3` ✅ — correct preorder!

The stack always returns the **most recently postponed** right child first (LIFO) — which is exactly the next node preorder needs, since preorder finishes the deepest/most recent left branch before backing up to older postponed branches.
